#!ctsdata
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.1|Alongside the ships the other best men of the Panachaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.2|slept all night long, subdued by gentle sleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.3|but not the son of Atreus, Agamemnon, the shepherd of the warriors—
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.4|sweet sleep did not hold him, as he pondered many things in his mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.5|As when the husband of Hera with her beautiful hair hurls lightning, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.6|creating an indescribable amount of rain or hail
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.7|or falling snow, when snow sprinkles the fields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.8|or the great jaws of crowded battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.9|so did the groans in the breast of Agamemnon come thick and fast 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.10|from the bottom of his heart, and his insides were trembling. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.11|Whenever he gazed out at the Trojan plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.12|he was amazed at the many fires that burned before Ilium,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.13|and at the shout of flutes and of pipes and the clamor of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.14|And then when he looked at the ships and the Achaean warriors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.15|over and over he tore hair from his head by the roots 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.16|to Zeus on high, and he groaned greatly in his glorious heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.17|This is the plan that seemed best to his liking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.18|to go first to Nestor first among the men, the descendant of Neleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.19|to find out if he could construct a faultless scheme 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.20|which might ward off evil for all the Danaans. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.21|Standing up he put on a khiton around his chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.22|and under his shining feet he fastened fine sandals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.23|and then around himself he put on the red-gold skin of a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.24|that was big and tawny—the skin reached all the way to his feet—and he took a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.25|In much the same way trembling held Menelaos—not for him either 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.26|did sleep sit on the eyelids—for fear that something would happen to 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.27|the Argives, those who for his sake over much water 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.28|had come to Troy, pondering bold war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.29|First he wrapped his broad back in a leopard skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.30|that was intricately patterned, and then he took up a helmet and on his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.31|he placed it, it was bronze, and then he took a spear in his mighty hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.32|He set out to go and get his brother up, who greatly over all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.33|the Argives was lord, and who was honored like a god by his people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.34|He found him putting the fine war gear around his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.35|next to the stern of the ship, and his coming was welcome to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.36|Menelaos well-known for his battle-cry addressed him first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.37|“Why ever, dear brother, are you arming yourself like this? Is there some one of our comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.38|that you will urge on to spy against the Trojans? But I am terribly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.39|afraid that no one will undertake this task,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.40|to spy on enemy men, going out alone 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.41|through the ambrosial night. He is going to have to be especially bold-hearted.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.42|The ruler Agamemnon answered him and said,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.43|“We have need of a plan, you and I, Menelaos nurtured by the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.44|a wily plan that will protect and save 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.45|the Argives and the ships, since the intentions of Zeus have turned. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.46|I see that he paid more attention to the sacrifices of Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.47|For I have not ever seen myself or ever heard anyone tell about
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.48|a single man devising so many astounding deeds in one day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.49|as many as Hektor who is dear to Zeus has done to the sons of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.50|just as he is, neither the beloved son of a goddess nor of a god. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.51|How many deeds he has accomplished I say will be on the mind of the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.52|for a long time into the future. For he has masterminded so many evils against the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.53|But go now and call Ajax and Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.54|running swiftly alongside the ships. And I to radiant Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.55|will go, and I will stir him to get up, if he is willing 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.56|to go to the sacred post of the watchmen and give commands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.57|Him they would especially heed. For his son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.58|gives the signals to the watchmen, together with the attendant of Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.59|Meriones. We have turned to them most of all.” 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.60|Menelaos well-known for his battle-cry then answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.61|“What do you command with your words and what are you telling me to do?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.62|Should I stay out there among the watchmen and wait until you come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.63|or should I run back after you, once I have duly commanded them?”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.64|Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon addressed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.65|“Wait there, so that we don’t somehow miss each other 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.66|coming and going. For there are many paths throughout the encamped mass of warriors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.67|Call out wherever you go, and command them to wake up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.68|naming each man together with the names of his ancestry and family,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.69|conferring radiant glory on all of them. Don’t be too proud in your heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.70|but let’s even us perform this labor. For surely on us 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.71|Zeus sent this heavy evil when we were born.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.72|So he spoke and he sent away his brother having duly commanded him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.73|He set out to go after Nestor, the shepherd of the warriors. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.74|He found him next to his shelter and the black ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.75|on a soft bed. His intricately patterned war gear lay beside him, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.76|a shield and two spears and a shining helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.77|Also next to him lay a belt that gleamed all over, which the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.78|used to wear, whenever he armed himself for battle that brings death to men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.79|leading the warriors, since he did not yield before woeful old age. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.80|Raising himself up on his elbow and lifting his head 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.81|he addressed the son of Atreus and questioned him with his words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.82|“Who are you, coming along the ships among the encamped mass of warriors all alone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.83|through the dark night, when other mortals are sleeping?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.84|Are you looking for one of your mules or one of your comrades?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.85|Call out—don’t come up on me in silence. What need has come upon you?” 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.86|The lord of men Agamemnon then answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.87|“Nestor, descendent of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.88|you will recognize me, the son of Atreus, Agamemnon, on whom above all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.89|Zeus has sent continuous labors, as long as the breath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.90|remains in my chest and my knees continue to rise. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.91|I am wandering like this, since not on my eyes does sweet sleep 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.92|sit, but war and worry for the Achaeans are on my mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.93|I am terribly afraid for the Danaans, nor is my heart 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.94|steady, but I am distraught, and my heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.95|leaps from my chest, and my shining limbs tremble beneath me. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.96|But if you want to take action, since sleep does not come to you either,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.97|let’s go to the watchmen, so that we can see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.98|if they, overcome by exhaustion and sleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.99|have gone to bed, and have altogether forgotten their watch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.100|Hostile men sit near, nor do we know that 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.101|they are not plotting to somehow fight even during the night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.102|The Gerenian horseman Nestor answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.103|“Son of Atreus most glorious, lord of men Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.104|surely Zeus the deviser will not bring all of Hektor’s intentions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.105|to fulfillment, as many as he is now hoping for. But I think that he will 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.106|be burdened with even more cares, if Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.107|turns his dear heart away from painful fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.108|But yes I will follow you. Also, let’s once again wake the others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.109|the son of Tydeus famed for his spear and Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.110|and swift Ajax and the resolute son of Phyles. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.111|But if someone else could go after and call these men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.112|Ajax who is a match for a god and lord Idomeneus—
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.113|for their ships are the furthest, not at all near.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.114|But although he is dear and I respect him, Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.115|I must quarrel with, even if you resent me for it. I can’t conceal it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.116|since he is sleeping, and he has turned the labor over to you alone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.117|Right now among all the best men he ought to be laboring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.118|to beseech them. For a need has come upon us that can’t be endured any longer.” 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.119|Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon addressed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.120|“Old man, I urge you to find fault with him at other times,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.121|for often he slacks off, and is not willing to labor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.122|not because he is yielding to caution or a thoughtless mind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.123|but looking to me and waiting for my initiative.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.124|But this time he has woken up long before me and stood over me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.125|Him I have sent to call the ones you are asking about. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.126|But let’s go. We will find those men before the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.127|among the watchmen, where I have told them to gather.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.128|Then the Gerenian horseman Nestor answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.129|“No one will feel indignation or disobey,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.130|no one of the Argives that is, whenever you summon and command anyone.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.131|So he spoke and he put a khiton around his chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.132|and under his shining feet he fastened fine sandals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.133|Around himself he fastened a crimson cloak,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.134|folded double and intricate, and there was a bloom of thick curly wool upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.135|He took an unyielding spear, sharpened with a bronze point,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.136|and he set out to go through the ships of the of the bronze-wearing Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.137|First then Odysseus, the equivalent of Zeus in intelligence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.138|the Gerenian horseman Nestor roused from sleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.139|calling out. The sound of his voice instantly surrounded his mind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.140|and he came from the shelter and spoke words to them. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.141|“Why ever do you wander this way along the ships among the encamped mass of warriors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.142|through the ambrosial night? What need so great has come upon us?”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.143|The Gerenian horseman Nestor then answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.144|“Son of Laertes, descended from the gods, Odysseus of many devices,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.145|don’t feel indignation. Such sorrow has overwhelmed the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.146|But follow us, so that we may rouse another as well, with whom it is fitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.147|to make a plan whether we should flee or fight.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.148|So he spoke. Going into his shelter Odysseus who is crafty in many ways 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.149|put an intricately patterned shield around his shoulders and went with them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.150|They went to the son of Tydeus, Diomedes. They found him 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.151|outside of his shelter together with his armor, and around him his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.152|slept, and they had their shields under their heads. Their spears 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.153|were planted with the spearheads up, and far and wide the bronze 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.154|was shining, like the lightning of father Zeus. But the hero 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.155|slept, and under him was spread the skin of a wild ox, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.156|and under his head was spread a shining tapestry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.157|Standing next to him the Gerenian horseman Nestor roused him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.158|moving him with his foot, and he stirred him up and insulted him to his face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.159|“Wake up, son of Tydeus. Why do you slumber the whole night through?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.160|Don’t you perceive that the Trojans on the rise of the plain 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.161|are sitting near our ships, and only a small space keeps them back?”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.162|So he spoke and Diomedes leapt up especially quickly from sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.163|He spoke out and addressed to him winged words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.164|“You are intractable, old man. You at least never cease from labor. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.165|Aren’t there other sons of the Achaeans, younger men, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.166|who could then rouse each of the kings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.167|going back and forth everywhere? You are impossible, old man.”
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.168|Then in turn the Gerenian horseman Nestor addressed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.169|“All these things, friend, you have spoken in good measure,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.170|I have faultless children, and I have warriors 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.171|and cities from which some one could go back and forth and call them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.172|But an especially great need has overwhelmed the Achaeans. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.173|Since now for everyone it stands on a razor’s edge 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.174|whether it will be woeful destruction for the Achaeans or life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.175|But come now, go make the swift Ajax and the son of Phyleus 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.176|get up—since you are younger—if you pity me.” 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.177|So he spoke, and around his shoulders Diomedes put the skin of a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.178|that was big and tawny—the skin reached all the way to his feet—and he took a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.179|He set out to go, and after getting them up the hero led them from their places.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.180|When they were mixed among the gathered watchmen, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.181|they found the leaders of the watch not sleeping, 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.182|but all sat awake with their weapons. 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.183|As when dogs keep a hard watch around flocks in an enclosure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.184|after hearing the sound of a beast with a powerful heart in the woods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.185|coming through the mountains, and there is a great commotion over it 
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.186|of men and dogs, and for them sleep is lost,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.187|just so sweet sleep was lost from the eyelids
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.188|of those keeping watch that evil night. For always toward the plain
