urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.565|laughing. The other Achaeans went together with him exulting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.566|When they reached the well-made tent of the son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.567|they tied up the horses with the well-cut reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.568|at the horses’ manger, where the horses of Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.569|stood, swift-footed, eating the honey-sweet wheat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.570|Into the ship’s stern went the blood-stained spoils from Dolon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.571|Odysseus placed them there, until he could prepare the sacred dedication to Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.572|They washed off the heavy sweat from themselves in the sea:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.573|going in, they washed around their shins, necks, and thighs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.574|And when the waves of the sea washed the heavy sweat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.575|washed it from their skin and cooled their own hearts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.576|they entered the well-fashioned baths and bathed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.577|Once the two had bathed and anointed themselves richly with olive oil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.578|they sat down to a meal, and to Athena from the mixing-bowl
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.due_ebbott:10.579|that was full, drawing off the honey-sweet wine, they poured libations.

